                <fr:title text="Invariant subspace">Invariant subspace</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>definition</fr:taxon>
                <fr:meta name="source"><fr:link href="/axler-1996-linear/" title="Linear Algebra Done Right" uri="http://localhost:8000/axler-1996-linear/" display-uri="axler-1996-linear" type="local">Linear Algebra Done Right</fr:link> Definition 5.2</fr:meta>
                <fr:meta name="source"><fr:link href="/lankham-2016-linear/" title="Linear algebra as an introduction to abstract mathematics" uri="http://localhost:8000/lankham-2016-linear/" display-uri="lankham-2016-linear" type="local">Linear algebra as an introduction to abstract mathematics</fr:link> Definition 7.1.1</fr:meta>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V]]></fr:tex> be a vector space over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex>. Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L\in \mathcal {L}(V)]]></fr:tex> be a linear operator on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V]]></fr:tex>. We call a subspace <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U\subseteq  V]]></fr:tex> <html:dfn>Invariant</html:dfn> under <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex> if for each <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u\in  U]]></fr:tex> we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L(u)\in  U]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
                <html:p>That is to say, the image of every vector in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U]]></fr:tex> under <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex> remains in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U]]></fr:tex>. So <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L(U)\subseteq  U]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
