                <fr:meta name="source"><fr:link href="/lankham-2016-linear/" title="Linear algebra as an introduction to abstract mathematics" uri="http://localhost:8000/lankham-2016-linear/" display-uri="lankham-2016-linear" type="local">Linear algebra as an introduction to abstract mathematics</fr:link> Definition 7.1.1</fr:meta>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V]]></fr:tex> be a vector space over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex>. Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L\colon  V\to  V]]></fr:tex> be a linear operator on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V]]></fr:tex>. Then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\lambda \in \mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex> is an <html:dfn>Eigenvalue</html:dfn> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex> if there is a non-zero vector <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u\in  V]]></fr:tex> such that
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[L(u)=\lambda  u.]]></fr:tex>
The vector <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u]]></fr:tex> is called an <html:dfn>Eigenvector</html:dfn> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex> corresponding to eigenvalue <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\lambda ]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
                <html:p>Compare this to the <fr:link href="/ela-001P/" title="Eigenvalue and Eigenvector of linear operator" uri="http://localhost:8000/ela-001P/" display-uri="ela-001P" type="local">notion</fr:link> in elementary linear algebra.</html:p>
